1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:02,095
By January 1986, the Space Shuttle had

2
00:00:02,095 --> 00:00:04,158
flown twenty-four times.

3
00:00:05,120 --> 00:00:06,883
Each flight reinforced one idea —

4
00:00:06,923 --> 00:00:08,365
the system worked.

5
00:00:09,367 --> 00:00:11,040
Across those flights, engineers

6
00:00:11,040 --> 00:00:12,712
documented O-ring damage.

7
00:00:13,493 --> 00:00:15,707
Erosion, blow-by — hot gas past seals

8
00:00:15,707 --> 00:00:17,922
designed to hold.

9
00:00:18,763 --> 00:00:20,105
Low-temperature flights all showed

10
00:00:20,105 --> 00:00:21,448
distress.

11
00:00:21,428 --> 00:00:23,251
But each flight survived, and the

12
00:00:23,251 --> 00:00:25,074
warning lost force.

13
00:00:26,155 --> 00:00:27,739
Danger became a known condition.

14
00:00:28,480 --> 00:00:30,382
A stop signal became a line item.

15
00:00:31,425 --> 00:00:33,188
The night before Challenger, engineers

16
00:00:33,188 --> 00:00:34,951
recommended against launch.

17
00:00:35,953 --> 00:00:36,975
The burden shifted —

18
00:00:37,034 --> 00:00:38,830
instead of proving it safe to fly,

19
00:00:38,830 --> 00:00:40,627
they were asked to prove it was

20
00:00:40,627 --> 00:00:42,423
unsafe.

21
00:00:43,417 --> 00:00:45,307
On the coldest morning the program had

22
00:00:45,307 --> 00:00:47,198
ever faced, seventy-three seconds was

23
00:00:47,198 --> 00:00:49,088
all the physics needed.

24
00:00:49,149 --> 00:00:51,353
The warning was never missing.

25
00:00:52,295 --> 00:00:53,227
It had been made survivable for too

26
00:00:53,227 --> 00:00:54,159
long.

27
00:00:54,942 --> 00:00:57,527
Small causes, massive consequences.
